{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492992"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1199"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1199"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.14,0.34,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69195"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1199"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69195"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of sudden-onset abdominal pain associated with vomiting. The pain radiates to the back. He has been admitted to the hospital twice in the past six months for similar episodes of pain and was treated with conservative management. He is a known heavy drinker. On examination, epigastric tenderness is noted on palpation. Rigidity and guarding are negative. A chest radiograph and an ECG are unremarkable. An abdominal ultrasound shows an enlarged and hypoechoic pancreas. Gallstones are not visualised. Some laboratory investigations are available (\u003Ca class=\u0022vdd-added\u0022 href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/PFynME3Kwup5gRocWkwXqoTtutnpDK.jpg\u0022\u003EImage 1\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca class=\u0022vdd-added\u0022 href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/eZqnZCO9UGfsKM4x2sJOojSO46Q2bu.jpg\u0022\u003E2\u003C/a\u003E). The diagnosis made here is acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would provide the most accurate assessment of the severity of his illness at this moment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ranson criteria","Glasgow prognostic criteria","APACHE II score","Amsterdam criteria","Balthazar score"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis alcoholic patient with epigastric pain radiating to the back and classical ultrasonographic findings (eg, hypoechoic and enlarged pancreas) most likely has acute pancreatitis. The severity of pancreatitis ranges from mild to severe. Several scoring systems have been developed to predict the severity of pancreatitis to help in making clinical decisions about further management. The most commonly used scoring system that has shown highest accuracy for predicting severe disease as compared to other scoring systems is \u003Cstrong\u003EAPACHE II\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Escore\u003C/strong\u003E which uses age, physiological parameters, and chronic conditions to give a score that establishes the pancreatitis severity. APACHE II has an excellent negative predictive value with a moderate positive predictive value. A score of \u22658 being predictive of a severe episode. One of the advantages of the APACHE II score is that it can be measured at the time of admission and repeated multiple times.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the APACHE II score was originally devised as a general measure of disease severity of patients in the intensive care unit, it is now used at different stages of a patient\u0027s hospitalisation and particularly in the emergency department. This score can be used at various stages through a patient\u0027s stay in hospital as a predictor of their health and the need for any diagnostic or therapeutic interventions. The accuracy of the APACHE II at admission as an early prognostic indicator of disease severity in acute pancreatitis is about 75%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERanson and Glasgow prognostic criteria have a limitation that they cannot fully predict the prognosis before 48 hours of admission. This patient has been admitted recently and APACHE II is a better scoring system for assessing the severity of his pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmsterdam criteria is used to predict patients who are at increased risk of genetic mutations that can cause Lynch syndrome. It is not used for acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBalthazar score is a scoring system for grading the severity of pancreatitis based on CT scan findings. This patient has not yet had a CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The APACHE II scoring system facilitates early assessment of the severity of an episode of pancreatitis.","APACHE II score can be calculated at admission and repeated multiple times during hospitalisation."],"references":["Shah AP, Mourad MM, Bramhall SR. Acute pancreatitis: current perspectives on diagnosis and management. J Inflamm Res. 2018;11:77-85. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5849938/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1199"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20454"},{"type":"media","id":"20455"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20454"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PFynME3Kwup5gRocWkwXqoTtutnpDK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PFynME3Kwup5gRocWkwXqoTtutnpDK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":305}},{"type":"media","id":"20455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20455"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eZqnZCO9UGfsKM4x2sJOojSO46Q2bu.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eZqnZCO9UGfsKM4x2sJOojSO46Q2bu.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":248}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T12:02:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T21:17:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1199"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69195"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"